{{distinguish|Artist collective}} An '''artist cooperative''' (also [[co-operative]] or co-op) is an autonomous [[visual arts]] organization, enterprise, or association jointly owned and democratically controlled by its members.<ref>[http://www.ica.coop/coop/principles.html International Co-operative Alliance ''Statement on the Co-operative Identity''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204081503/http://www.ica.coop/coop/principles.html |date=2012-02-04 }}.</ref> Artist cooperatives are legal entities organized as non-capital stock [[corporations]], [[non-profit organizations]], or [[voluntary association|unincorporated associations]]. Such cooperatives typically provide professional facilities and services for its artist-members, including studios, workshops, equipment, exhibition galleries, and educational resources.<ref>[http://www.sfc.ucdavis.edu/cooperatives/whatis.html#arts Small Farm Center, University of California] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305050618/http://www.sfc.ucdavis.edu/cooperatives/whatis.html#arts |date=March 5, 2009 }}.</ref> By design, all economic and non-economic benefits and liabilities of the cooperative are shared equally among its members. Cooperative members elect their board of directors from within the membership.<ref>[http://www.ncba.coop/abcoop.cfm National Cooperative Business Association] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218093223/http://www.ncba.coop/abcoop.cfm |date=February 18, 2009 }}.</ref>
