{{one source|date=October 2014}} [[File:Jan lukas kracker portret.jpg|thumb|200px|Self-portrait in a mural at the Abbey of [[Nová Říše]] (1766)]] [[File:Johann Lucas Kracker - St. Francis of Solano Baptizing Indians - WGA12268.jpg|thumb|225px|[[Francis Solanus|Saint Francis of Solano]] Baptizing the Indians (1770); in the Bishopric Seminary, Eger]] '''Johann Lucas Kracker''', also '''Jan Lukáš Kracker''' or '''János Lukács Kracker''' (3 March 1717, [[Vienna]] - 1 December 1779, [[Eger]]) was an Austrian-Czech painter of the late [[Baroque art|Baroque]] period. His work consisted mostly of ceiling or wall [[fresco]]es and altarpieces.
== Life == His family originally came from [[Bohemia]] and his father, Josef Kracker (1683–1733), was a sculptor. He received his first training with Anton Hertzog (1692–1740) and continued at the [[Academy of Fine Arts Vienna]] after 1738, where his teachers included [[Paul Troger]] and [[Michelangelo Unterberger]].<ref name="N">{{NDB|12|632|632|Kracker, Johann Lucas|Klára Garas|122638417}}</ref> His first frescoes, created for the Schlosskirche St. Martin ([[Graz]]) in 1742, have not survived.
Initially, he was employed at a workshop in [[Brno]], later becoming independent and working throughout [[Moravia]], briefly settling in [[Znojmo]], where he got married. He then moved on to [[Upper Hungary]] in 1754, where he worked in [[Šaštín-Stráže|Šaštín]] and [[Prešov]] (both now in [[Slovakia]]).<ref name="N" /> From 1760 to 1761, he was in Prague where, despite objections from the Prague Painters' Guild, he executed frescoes at the Church of St. Nikolaus in [[Malá Strana]]. From 1762 to 1764, he painted at the Monastery and the [[Premonstratensians|Premonstratensian]] Church in [[Jasov]].<ref name="N" />
In 1767, he settled in Eger. Bishop {{ill|Karl von Esterhazy|hu|Eszterházy Károly}} commissioned him to do work for the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Eger|Diocese of Eger]] and at the Bishop's properties. Three years later, he created the altarpiece for the "Minoritenkirche" ([[Franciscan|Franciscan Church]]) and in 1777 he produced his masterpiece depicting the [[Council of Trent]] at the Líceum.<ref name="N" /> He remained in the Bishop's service for the rest of his life, although he occasionally travelled to execute small commissions elsewhere.
