'''Readergirlz''' is an [[virtual community|online book community]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/index.asp?layout=article&articleid=CA6422606&talk_back_header_id=6422606#talkBack|title=An Online Book Club|last=Burling|first=Alexis|date=2008-03-08|work=Publishers Weekly|publisher=Reed Business Information|accessdate=2009-04-22|archivedate=2009-04-21|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gDG7OX3O}}</ref> that is an advocate for [[literacy]] in [[teenage]] girls. The site was founded on March 1, 2007<ref name="SeattlePI">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/books/304068_readergirlz20.html?source=rss|title=Local authors hope 'Readergirlz' site helps create women of substance|last=Goodnow|first=Cecelia|date=2007-02-20|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|publisher=Hearst Seattle Media|accessdate=2009-04-22|archivedate=2009-04-21|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gDFX1as6}}</ref> by Dia Calhoun, Janet Lee Carey, Lorie Ann Grover, and Justina Chen Headley.<ref name="SeattleTimes">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/living/2003586219_readergirlz24.html|title="Gutsy" girl books — and beyond|last=Dunnewind|first=Stephanie|date=2007-02-24|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=2009-04-22|archivedate=2009-04-21|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gDFm6sNb}}</ref> The site is a partner of the [[Young Adult Library Services Association]]. Readergirlz hosts authors monthly for an exchange with teens and administers special literacy projects, including the support of Teen Read Week, the third week of October, and Support Teen Literature Day in April.
